    { "risk": "HYPOTHESIS 1 (MOST LIKELY): One or more external APIs have degraded. The carrier rates API is the prime suspect — carrier aggregation services often degrade gradually as they add backend carriers or experience upstream issues. A 1600ms increase maps cleanly to one API adding ~1.5s to its response time.", "severity": "critical", "mitigation": "Immediately instrument per-dependency response times (even temporary logging). Check external API status pages and changelogs for the past 2 weeks. Add explicit timeouts (e.g., 500ms for geocoding, 1s for rates, 1s for payment) with fallback behavior." },
    { "risk": "HYPOTHESIS 2 (LIKELY): Connection pool or thread pool exhaustion as a secondary effect. Even a modest slowdown in one external API can cause in-flight requests to hold connections longer, gradually saturating the pool. This creates a compounding effect where healthy requests queue behind slow ones.", "severity": "high", "mitigation": "Check connection pool metrics (active vs. idle connections over time). Verify HTTP client connection pool sizes and timeout configurations. Look for thread pool queue depth increases." },
    { "risk": "HYPOTHESIS 3 (MODERATE): Sequential external API calls where parallel is possible. If geocoding, rates, and payment are called sequentially and one has degraded, the total latency is the sum. If called in parallel where possible, only the slowest matters.", "severity": "high", "mitigation": "Audit the request handler code path. If geocoding → rates is sequential but could be parallelized (geocoding result not needed for rates), restructure to parallel calls." },
    { "risk": "HYPOTHESIS 4 (MODERATE): DNS resolution or TLS handshake degradation for external endpoints. Gradual DNS TTL changes or certificate chain validation issues can add latency without causing errors.", "severity": "medium", "mitigation": "Check DNS resolution times to external API hosts. Verify TLS handshake times. Consider DNS caching or connection keep-alive to amortize these costs." },
