    { "risk": "HYPOTHESIS 7 (RULED OUT): Deployment-related regression. Team confirms gradual onset unrelated to deployments.", "severity": "low", "mitigation": "No action needed unless deployment timeline is re-examined and found to correlate." },
    { "risk": "No per-dependency observability exists, making this class of issue invisible until users complain", "severity": "critical", "mitigation": "This is the systemic issue. Regardless of root cause, the inability to see per-dependency latency is an architectural gap that must be closed permanently." }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Three-phase response: (1) IMMEDIATE TRIAGE — Add temporary per-external-API latency logging to isolate which dependency degraded. This is a 30-minute change that provides the definitive answer. Log the wall-clock time for each outbound HTTP call individually. (2) SHORT-TERM FIX — Once the degraded API is identified: add explicit connect and read timeouts to all three external API clients (suggest 500ms connect, 2s read as starting points), add a circuit breaker (e.g., fail-open with cached/default response after N consecutive slow calls), and parallelize external calls where data dependencies allow. (3) LONG-TERM HARDENING — Add structured per-dependency latency metrics (histograms, not just averages) to a monitoring dashboard. Add geocoding response caching (addresses rarely change). Implement the bulkhead pattern so one slow dependency cannot exhaust shared connection pools. Add SLO-based alerting: if P99 for any external dependency exceeds its budget, alert before end-to-end latency is impacted.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "Add per-dependency timing instrumentation to the HTTP client layer or request handler",
      "Add timeout configuration to all external API client constructors",
      "Add circuit breaker middleware/wrapper around external API calls",
      "Create or update monitoring dashboard with per-dependency latency panels",
      "Add geocoding response cache (Redis or in-memory with TTL)"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Circuit Breaker (Hystrix/Resilience4j pattern) for external calls. Bulkhead pattern to isolate connection pools per dependency. Timeout pattern with explicit connect and read timeouts. Cache-aside pattern for geocoding. Structured observability with per-dependency latency histograms tagged by dependency name.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "Do NOT add retries without timeouts — retrying a slow call without a timeout doubles the latency",
      "Do NOT set aggressive timeouts without fallback behavior — failing fast is only useful if you can degrade gracefully",
      "Do NOT assume the database dashboard is showing the full picture — verify it shows P99 and includes all query types",
      "Do NOT parallelize calls that have data dependencies (e.g., if carrier rates need geocoded coordinates, those must remain sequential)",
      "Do NOT add caching for payment gateway calls — these are transactional and must always be live",
      "Do NOT ignore connection pool configuration — default pool sizes are often too small and become the hidden bottleneck"
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 82,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "External API degradation is the primary root cause — the evidence profile (gradual, no deployment, no errors, normal DB) is a textbook signature",
      "Lack of per-dependency observability is the systemic gap that allowed this to go undetected",
      "Circuit breakers and timeouts are the correct architectural remediation regardless of which specific API degraded"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Which specific external API is degrading — cannot determine without instrumentation data (carrier rates API is the prime suspect based on typical degradation patterns)",
      "Whether connection pool exhaustion is a compounding factor — need pool metrics to confirm",
      "Whether calls are sequential or parallel — need to see the actual code path"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "The database dashboard is accurately reporting query latency (showing P99, not just average)",
      "No infrastructure changes (network, DNS, load balancer) occurred in the past 2 weeks",
      "The 10K requests/day is relatively stable — not a growing traffic pattern",
      "External API calls are made synchronously within the request lifecycle (not queued asynchronously)",
      "No retry logic exists that could be amplifying slow external responses"
    ]
  }
}

